				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Film Explores Cura&ccedil;ao&#8217;s Effort to Become a Caribbean Haven for Coral</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Andrew C. Revkin			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-05-13T21:16:13+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 13, 2015 5:16 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 13, 2015 5:16 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/13/a-film-explores-curaaos-effort-to-become-a-caribbean-haven-for-coral/" data-title="A Film Explores Cura&ccedil;ao&#8217;s Effort to Become a Caribbean Haven for Coral" data-description="A documentary explores how Curacao is trying to lead the Caribbean in building an economy around its coral reefs, instead one that threatens them.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracao-coral/dotcuracao-coral-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracao-coral/dotcuracao-coral-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracao-coral/dotcuracao-coral-blog480.jpg" id="100000003681784" width="480" height="302" alt="Coral reefs offÂ CuraÃ§ao&#039;s eastern end - calledÂ East Point or Oostpunt - are among the richest in the Caribbean."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="302"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Coral reefs offÂ CuraÃ§ao's eastern end - calledÂ East Point or Oostpunt - are among the richest in the Caribbean.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Carmabi Foundation</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t14h4s" class="update">Updated | </span></webonly> After months of reporting and planning, a frenetic week of filming in March, and many long nights in the editing suite, 10 Pace University communication students, with guidance from Prof. Maria Luskay and me, have completed â<a title="Curacao's Coral Challenge" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Py9xpwhoBuI">CuraÃ§aoâs Coral Challenge â Reviving the Rain Forests of the Sea</a>.â</p>
<div class="w480">
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="Py9xpwhoBuI" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/Py9xpwhoBuI/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The film had its premiere on May 12 the Jacob Burns Film Center, in Pleasantville, N.Y., and will be soon be broadcast on <a href="//www.telecuracao.com/web/homepage.aspx">TeleCuracao</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The 25-minute documentaryÂ outlines how this Caribbean island nation, tucked a few dozen miles from the South American coast and <a href="//www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-17290626">long a refining hub for Venezuelan oil</a>, is struggling to expand tourism but do so without degrading a prime asset drawing visitors &#8212; its coral reefs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the film, marine biologists from the 60-year-old <a href="//www.researchstationcarmabi.org/">Carmabi Research Institute</a>, <a href="//www.secore.org/site/our-work/detail/project-curacao.2.html">Secore Foundation</a> and <a href="//curacao.waittinstitute.org/">Waitt Institute</a> explain why the island&#8217;s geography and other factors have fortuitously preserved remarkably vibrant reefs in some spots despite decades of pollution, cruise ship traffic and coastal construction.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I think that CuraÃ§aoÂ has been really lucky so far,&#8221; we were told by <a href="//ayanaelizabeth.com/about/bio/">Ayana Elizabeth Johnson</a>, a marine biologist who did her doctoral research on <a href="//cmbc.ucsd.edu/People/Students/johnson-ayana/_nebk_index.php">fishing practices around coral reefs</a> on the island and now runs the Waitt Institute, a conservation group helping Caribbean islands develop &#8220;Blue Halo&#8221;Â <a href="//voices.nationalgeographic.com/2013/12/16/3-steps-to-ocean-zoning/">marine zoning plans</a>Â designed to allow communities to âuse the ocean without using it up.â</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment/dotcuracaocoastdevelopment-blog480.jpg" id="100000003681773" width="480" height="290" alt="Conservationists inÂ CuraÃ§ao are trying to prevent coastal development, like this near a bay called Spanish Water, in areas with rich reefs."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="290"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Conservationists inÂ CuraÃ§ao are trying to prevent coastal development, like this near a bay called Spanish Water, in areas with rich reefs.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Zoning for the Seas</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the film, Johnson says that shielding the most important reefs from fishing and runoff is a critical step or the island&#8217;s luck will run out:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-55048"></span></p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">CuraÃ§ao has some of the healthiest reefs in the Caribbean, and that is not because of marine reserves, thatâs not because of strong pollution controls, itâs not because coastal development hasnât happened,&#8221; Johnson says in the film. &#8220;It is because of great currents that flush pollution out, itâs because the north shore hasnât been developed just because itâs not the type of typography that lends itself to that, so figuring out how to transition from luck to deliberately protecting the reefs is the [challenge]Â right now.&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The first Blue HaloÂ initiative was launchedÂ in Barbuda in 2012 and recently produced pioneeringÂ ocean zoningÂ legislation there. CuraÃ§ao, along with Montserrat,Â <a href="//voices.nationalgeographic.com/2015/02/26/blue-halo-initiative-expands-to-montserrat-and-curacao/">signed agreements with the institute in February</a>.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/21/blogs/dotbarbudamap/dotbarbudamap-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/21/blogs/dotbarbudamap/dotbarbudamap-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/08/21/blogs/dotbarbudamap/dotbarbudamap-blog480.jpg" id="100000003068177" width="480" height="379" alt="A map of &lt;a href=&quot;//barbuda.waittinstitute.org/description/&quot;&gt;protected marine zones&lt;/a&gt;Â that are being established around the Caribbean island of Barbuda."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="379"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A map of <a href="//barbuda.waittinstitute.org/description/">protected marine zones</a>Â that are being established around the Caribbean island of Barbuda.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Waitt Institute</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The initiative, Johnson explains, is a tool kit that &#8220;includes things like habitat mapping, ecological assessment, policy development, education, communication, enforcement training.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Waitt Institute came toÂ CuraÃ§ao because it is much larger than Barbuda and has already demonstrated an interest in conservation through existing laws governing fishing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;We didnât want to just work on small islands,&#8221; she says in the film. &#8220;And CuraÃ§ao was our big leap to see how we can help a place like this that is a lot more complicated but also has a lot more local capacity.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Generating public support for such environmental stepsÂ can be difficult in the face ofÂ conflicting priorities and unrelated political problems. Curcacao, largelyÂ independent ofÂ the Netherlands since 2010, has <a href="//www.csmonitor.com/World/Americas/2013/0702/Curacao-small-island-big-problems">experienced political growing pains</a> in recent years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We interviewed tourism officials who expressed caution about clamping down too much on development, given the lack of growth in other economic sectors, and fisherman concerned that no-fishing zones could end fishing altogether &#8212;Â saying local fisherman aren&#8217;t the main problem and are already facing high fuel costs and competition from cheaper seafood imports.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But we found a general sense of optimism that a reasonable balance can be struck.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Among the filmâs other interview subjects are <a href="//www.parlamento.cw/members/154/">Glenn Sulvaran</a>, a member of CuraÃ§aoâs parliament with a passion for reef conservation; <a href="https://lightscameracoral.wordpress.com/2015/03/20/tourism-development-and-sustainability-three-sides-of-curacao/">Faisal Dilrosun</a>, a government health and environment advisor; and Carmabi Institute science director <a href="//www.researchstationcarmabi.org/associate-scientists/dr-mark-vermeij">Mark Vermeij</a>.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/04/blogs/dotparrotfish/dotparrotfish-articleInline.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/04/blogs/dotparrotfish/dotparrotfish-articleInline.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/07/04/blogs/dotparrotfish/dotparrotfish-articleInline.jpg" id="100000002982004" width="190" height="116" alt="Overfishing of parrotfish (at right in trap), which graze on algae, is a prime factor threatening coral reefs in the Caribbean, according to &lt;a href=&quot;//www.iucn.org/?16050&quot; title=&quot;IUCN report on coral threats&quot;&gt;a new international report.&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="116"><meta itemprop="width" content="190"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Overfishing of parrotfish (at right in trap), which graze on algae, is a prime factor threatening coral reefs in the Caribbean, according to <a href="//www.iucn.org/?16050" title="IUCN report on coral threats">a new international report.</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> IUCN</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The film grew out of reporting I did last year on encouraging report from the International Union for Conservation of Nature and other groups <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/04/protecting-parrotfish-on-the-path-to-a-caribbean-reef-revival/">laying out ways to sustain Caribbean coral reefs</a> even in the face of rising temperatures and other impacts of human-driven global warming. One vital step is protecting parrotfish and other algae-munching herbivores.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Reef Protection Starts on Land</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But one theme that emerged in the reporting is that a reef revival cannot succeed unless it includes managingÂ activitiesÂ on <em>land</em> &#8212; the main source of nutrient-rich pollution. The film describes how excessive nutrients from sewage or agriculture can tip the balance in the perpetual &#8220;<a href="//www.esa.org/esa/in-the-turf-war-against-seaweed-coral-reefs-more-resilient-than-expected/">turf war</a>&#8221; between corals and algae that I first learned about from John Bruno at the University of North Carolina.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With that issue in mind, Vermeij and the Carmabi Institute have been involved for years in delicate discussions related to the fate of a critical ecological and economic asset &#8212; a 17-square-mile tract of scrub, forest and grasslands called East Point (Oostpunt in Dutch) that constitutes 10 percent of CuraÃ§ao&#8217;s land area.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">East Point has been owned since the 1870s by the Maal family. The family and the CuraÃ§aoÂ government have been in court since the 1980s, tussling over how much of the land can be developed.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaonasa/dotcuracaonasa-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaonasa/dotcuracaonasa-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcuracaonasa/dotcuracaonasa-blog480.jpg" id="100000003681484" width="480" height="422" alt="The outermost tip of East Point, or Oostpunt, an undeveloped tract inÂ CuraÃ§ao ringed by rich reefs. The longtime landowner is negotiating with the government over its fate."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="422"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The outermost tip of East Point, or Oostpunt, an undeveloped tract inÂ CuraÃ§ao ringed by rich reefs. The longtime landowner is negotiating with the government over its fate.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> NASA</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.researchstationcarmabi.org/images/stories/file/Mark%20PDFs/Oostpunt/VVRP1112_Eastpoint%20Public%20Presentation-20121030-in%20progress%2020121025%20revised%2030%20Oct%202012%20DL%202012-11-13.pdf">Click here for a slide presentation</a> laying out the development proposal in 2012.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The familyâs views are best reflected in a speech given at <a href="//www.kkcuracao.info/?p=30109">a 2013 meeting</a> of the CuraÃ§ao Trade and BusinessÂ Association by Willem Pieter âWillyâ Maal (<a href="//curacaochronicle.com/economy/the-road-to-economic-recovery-the-oostpunt-scenario/">published in 2013 in the CuraÃ§aoÂ Chronicle</a>).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the speech, Maal â who is credited by many environmentalists with trying hard to prevent illegal fishing and other harmful activities &#8212; said the endless delays have harmed the environment and economy:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You cannot preserve a Rolls Royce by putting it in a shed on the coast, and not touch it, maintain it, or protect it!</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nature, left to its own recourse, will also ruin itself. Even worse, man, as part of that ânatureâ will destroy it even fasterâ¦. The natural richness and potential of Oostpunt since 1993 is under huge stress due to natural deterioration, and rampant illegal practices such as spear fishing, plundering of baby conch, lobsters and the capture of sea turtles and rays, poaching of goats/sheep and donkeys, while a variety of other criminal activities savagely take place in the area, like car theft and stripping, the smuggling of drugs and people, trash dumping, etc.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This destruction can only be stopped by durable and well-balanced responsible development of Oostpunt. This requires the re-zoning [of] Oostpunt according to logical, objective, professional on-site evaluationsâ¦.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After all, the Maal family are not developers. We are owners who want logical, objective sustainable guidelines that the future developers will have to adhere to. The fact is that the Maal family for centuries maintained and preserved this area, and never allowed piecemeal or bit-parcelization or undesirable projects.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">ConservationÂ groups, including Carmabi, have been <a href="//www.researchstationcarmabi.org/news/latest-news/113-information-on-oostpunt-including-carmabi-s-concerns-regarding-the-proposed-zoning-plan">pressing to limit the construction footprint</a> to avoid runoff and other harmful impacts on the fringing reefs â which are among the richest in the Caribbean and serve as a nursery for reefs along the coast as coral and fish larvae drift in currents. The film contains spectacular footage of those reefs shot by Carmabi divers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Carmabi Foundation has proposed <a href="//www.researchstationcarmabi.org/news/latest-news/113-information-on-oostpunt-including-carmabi-s-concerns-regarding-the-proposed-zoning-plan">an alternative development plan</a>.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/doteastpointplan/doteastpointplan-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/doteastpointplan/doteastpointplan-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/doteastpointplan/doteastpointplan-blog480.jpg" id="100000003681542" width="480" height="377" alt="A proposed plan for developing and conserving parts of East Point, or Oostpunt, a tract onÂ CuraÃ§ao that is fringed by some of the richest reefs in the Caribbean."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="377"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A proposed plan for developing and conserving parts of East Point, or Oostpunt, a tract onÂ CuraÃ§ao that is fringed by some of the richest reefs in the Caribbean.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Carmabi Foundation</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Hopefully, a compromise can be found that allows the Maal family to prosper while the coastal reef resource is preserved.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Learning by Doing</strong></p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/11/blogs/dotpaceteam/dotpaceteam-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/11/blogs/dotpaceteam/dotpaceteam-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/02/11/blogs/dotpaceteam/dotpaceteam-blog480.jpg" id="100000003504310" width="480" height="321" alt="Prof. Maria Luskay of Pace University (standing) and her student documentary team."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="321"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Prof. Maria Luskay of Pace University (standing) and her student documentary team.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Andrew C. Revkin</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I have loved co-teachingÂ this spring travel course, in which a mix of graduate and undergraduate students learn on two fronts. They tackle complex subjects &#8212; like balancing environmental and economic concerns &#8212; even as they seek to master the extraordinary but complicated hardware and software that have leveled the playing field of filmmaking so that students need not wait to be out in the ârealâ world to convey important stories.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Actually, students can still be in high school and contribute. Such is the case with Kayla Pacenka, the sister of Cassie Pacenka, the documentary&#8217;s lead editor and assistant director.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">KaylaÂ spent many hours, even while studying for finals, refining her <a href="//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adobe_After_Effects">After Effects</a> skills and creating the film&#8217;s animations and titles, which help explain reef economics and ecology.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You can track the production&#8217;s high points and headaches on the students&#8217; <a href="https://lightscameracoral.wordpress.com/">Lights, Camera, Coral</a> blog and in <a href="//j.mp/curacaocoralvlog">Cassie Pacenka&#8217;s vlog</a>.</p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcoralanimation/dotcoralanimation-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcoralanimation/dotcoralanimation-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/05/13/blogs/dotcoralanimation/dotcoralanimation-blog480.jpg" id="100000003682155" width="480" height="271" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="271"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Kayla Pacenka</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The course, created byÂ <a href="//www.pace.edu/dyson/academic-departments-and-programs/mediacomm/faculty/maria-luskay">Prof. Luskay</a>Â some 15 years ago, has made films about efforts to conserve natural resources since I joined her in 2011. Previous films in our environmental series have examinedÂ <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/19/exploring-the-social-and-environmental-challenges-as-brazil-prepares-for-two-sports-spectacles/">Brazilâs efforts to limit social and environmental impacts</a>Â from the World Cup and 2016 Summer Olympics;Â <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/05/08/can-technology-and-tourism-sustain-mexicos-sea-turtles/">sea turtle conservation</a>Â in Mexicoâs Baja region;Â theÂ <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/05/06/from-bark-to-bottle-a-cork-story/">sustainably managed cork forests</a>Â of Portugal; andÂ <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/05/14/farming-shrimp-with-the-planet-in-mind/">low-impact shrimp farmin</a>g in Belize.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I hope you&#8217;ll watch the film, weigh in on its conclusions and share it with friends or colleagues who care about ocean conservation.</p>
	</div>
